Theory¶

Thread vs Process¶

  • A process consists of multiple thread.
  • Threads are sub-units of a process.
  • Sharing data is difficult between process, but easy between thread under a same process.
  • Same number of processes consume more resource than threads.
  • Processes do not affect each other, but failure of one thread would crash the entire process
  • Same process can easily expand to multiple computer, but same thread is suitable for expanding on multiple core.
  • process can lock the memory adress when the other threads have to be pending until one of its thread use the sharing memory.
  • the memory usage of a process can be limited with setup

Parallelism paradigm¶

Parallelism has many different paradigm, including:

  • Single program, multiple data (SPMD) parallelism
  • Multiple program, multiple data (MPMD) parallelism
  • Message passing using MPI
  • Task farming
  • Data parallel
  • Combinations of these approaches
  • Custom user-defined approaches

Load balancing¶

Pool¶

为什么会有进程池的概念？ 当我们开启50个进程让他们都将100这个数减1次减到50，你会发现特别慢！

效率问题，原因：

1，开辟内存空间。因为每开启一个进程，都会开启一个属于这个进程池的内存空间，因为进程与进程之间数据是完全隔离的。

2，并且这些独立的内存空间会有许多寄存器，堆栈，文件等，他们存着这个进程里面的变量和数据等。所以生成这些东西都会耗时。

3，生成这么多进程，都需要系统调度，这个也会耗时。不仅这样，还会涉及到进程使用cpu的时候，当a进程使用一段时间cpu，b进程要去使用cpu，za和b中间的节点不仅要记录a进程执行到这，还要调用b进程之前执行的结果，所以在这个节点不仅涉及到cpu的切换，还涉及到寄存器，堆栈等包含的数据，还有内存空间的切换。

所以，我们不会无休止的去开启进程，而是设计一个池子，这个池子就是进程池。

进程池的含义？ python中的进程池，在你还没有创建进程之前，先创建一个属于进程的池子。这个池子指定能存放多少个进程，比如说5个进程，因此会先创建这5个进程。当任务进来的时候，比如说50个任务需要50个进程去处理，但是不会生成50个进程，而是排队去进程池里面拿进程处理任务，所以同一时刻最多有5个进程在处理任务，当任务处理完毕，不会将进程销毁，而是放回到进程池，在让其他任务进来让这些进程处理。

所以，进程池的优点有：

1，提高效率，节省开辟进程和开辟内存空间的时间及销毁进程的时间。

2，节省内存空间。

synchronous vs asynchronous¶

type definition Application function
synchronous execute a task after the previous task is completed - safe for tasks with dependencies,
but maybe long wait time		 ipyparallel.map_sync()
asynchronous execute a task regardless the status of previous task - unsafe for tasks with dependencies
- fast for independent task.		 ipyparallel.map_async()

pickle¶

  • pickle in Python is primarily used in serializing and deserializing a Python object structure. In other words, it's the process of converting a Python object into a byte stream (.pickle) to:
    • store it in a file/database,
    • maintain program state across sessions,
    • transport data over the network/process (.pickle is similar to .JSON，YAML，XML)
    • What can be pickled and unpickled?

Global Interpreter Lock¶

Python's multithreading cannot take advantage of multiple cores of a cpu:

  • The official interpreter of python is Cython, which uses the GIL (Global Interpreter Lock) lock when executing code.
  • This lock is acquired before any thread executes. The lock is global and only one, so a lock cannot be owned by two threads at the same time. The interpreter periodically releases the lock, and multiple threads use the lock in time-sharing. Therefore, only one thread holds the lock at a time (为什么Python多线程无法利用多核). The GIL was applied to improves the computation efficiency in the era of CPU with single logical core, but it limites python to utilize the power of CPU with multicore nowadays.
  • Effect: GIL might not affect I/O-heavy tasks, but badly limite the computation-heavy tasks.
  • Simple solution: Each core has only one activating thread at each moment. Each logical core/process own a GIL, and only one thread is distributed on each logical core.

Best practice¶

Trading off on computational complexity between time and memory:

  • Synchronously paralleling tasks on multiple threads under a same process reduces resource-consuming:
    • when tasks are dependent
    • when tasks sharing large data or many objects
  • Asynchronously paralleling tasks on multiple processes reduces computational time:
    • when tasks are independent
    • when tasks are computationally heavy

RandomForestClassifier( )¶

# make dataset
from sklearn.datasets import make_classification
X, y = make_classification(n_samples=10000, n_features=10,
                           n_informative=10, n_redundant=0,
                           random_state=0, shuffle=False)
# define function
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
def clf_fit_predict(X, y):
    clf = RandomForestClassifier(max_depth=10, random_state=0)
    clf = clf.fit(X, y)
    return clf.predict(X)

# setup for cluster profile
cluster = ipp.Cluster(n=5)
# starting engine by connecting a client with showing progress bar
rc = cluster.start_and_connect_sync()
# open controller
view = rc.direct_view()
# submit task to cluster and execute
result = view.apply_async(os.getpid)
# wait function execution with showing progress bar
result.wait_interactive()
# collect result
result = result.get_dict()
rc.shutdown(hub=True)
print(f'\n result: {result} \n')

architecture¶

The IPython architecture consists of four components:

  • Engine: an extension of the IPython kernel for Jupyter.
    • listens for requests over the network,
    • runs code, and
    • returns results
  • Hub: The center of an IPython cluster that keeps track of engine connections, schedulers, clients, as well as all task requests and results. The primary role of the Hub is to
    • facilitate queries of the cluster state, and
    • minimize the necessary information required to establish the many connections involved in connecting new clients and engines.
  • Schedulers: the processes provide a fully asynchronous function to a set of engines
  • Client: the Client class for connecting to a cluster.
    • allow users to interact with a set of engines through the ipyparallel interface.

Context manager¶

The Parallel processing in ipyparallel will walk throught the following steps:

  • Entering a Cluster context
    • starts the cluster
    • waits for engines to be ready
    • connects a client
    • returns the client
  • Exiting a Client context closes the client’s socket connections to the cluster.
  • Exiting a Cluster context shuts down all of the cluster’s resources.

The use of context managers is encouraged if the cluster is not longer needed after use. In ipyparallel, the Cluster and Client classes can be used as context managers. The context managers help to:

  • connect and disconnect clients
  • interacting with engines
  • easier cleanup of resources
In [10]:
# Cluster as Context manager
with ipp.Cluster(n=5) as rc: # setup for cluster profile, starting engine by connecting a client with showing progress bar
    # open controller
    dview = rc.direct_view() 
    # submit task to cluster and execute
    result = dview.apply_async(os.getpid)
    # wait function execution with showing progress bar
    result.wait_interactive()
    # collect result
    result = result.get_dict()
# at this point, the cluster processes have been shutdown
time.sleep(0.5)
print(f'\n result: {result} \n')

Controller¶

Controller: a collection of processes that provides an interface . The two primary models for interacting with engines are:

Controller model Definition Use case
DirectView class Engines are addressed explicitly 1) import package
2) upload function
3) The number of tasks and engines are equal.
LoadBalancedView class Scheduler is entrusted with assigning work to
appropriate engines in a destination-agnostic manner.		 1) run function
2) The number of tasks is more than the number of engines

Drect view¶

  • ipp.Client().direct_view(): A Direct interface, where engines are addressed explicitly
    • dview = rc[:]: use all engines
In [11]:
with ipp.Cluster(n=5) as rc:
    # upload funtion
    dview = rc.direct_view()
    dview.push({'HelloWorld': HelloWorld})
    result = dview.apply_async(HelloWorld)
    result.wait_interactive()
    result = result.get()
time.sleep(0.5)
print(f'\n result: {result} \n')

Load balanced view¶

  • load_balanced_view(): A LoadBalanced interface, where the Scheduler is entrusted with assigning work to appropriate engines
In [12]:
with ipp.Cluster(n=5) as rc:
    # upload funtion
    dview = rc.direct_view()
    dview.push({'HelloWorld': HelloWorld})
    lview = rc.load_balanced_view()
    result = lview.map_async(HelloWorld, np.arange(0,10))
    result.wait_interactive()
    result = result.get()
time.sleep(0.5)
print(f'\n result: {result} \n')

Example¶

single argument¶

In [13]:
with ipp.Cluster(n=5) as rc:
    dview = rc.direct_view()
    result1 = dview.apply_async(HelloWorld) # each engines run function without input arguments
    result2 = dview.apply_async(HelloWorld, np.arange(0,10)) # each engines run function with the entire object
    result3 = dview.map_async(HelloWorld, np.arange(0,10)) # the object are slided into single element and feed into the function
    result1.wait_interactive()
    result2.wait_interactive()
    result3.wait_interactive()
    result1 = result1.get()
    result2 = result2.get()
    result3 = result3.get()
time.sleep(0.5)
print(f'\n result1: {result1} \n')
print(f'\n result2: {result2} \n')
print(f'\n result3: {result3} \n')

multiple argument with partial filled¶

In [15]:
%%time
from functools import partial
# partially filled argument
def clf_fit_predict_partial(i, X, y):
    return clf_fit_predict(X, y)
# launch cluster
with ipp.Cluster(n=5) as rc:
    dview = rc.direct_view()
    # import package
    dview.execute("from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier")
    # upload function
    dview.push({'clf_fit_predict': clf_fit_predict, 
                'clf_fit_predict_partial': clf_fit_predict_partial})
    time.sleep(1) # give some time to upload
    # submit task and execute
    lview = rc.load_balanced_view()
    result = lview.map_async(partial(clf_fit_predict_partial, X = X, y = y), np.arange(0,15))
    result.wait_interactive()
    result = result.get()
time.sleep(0.5)
print(f'\n result: {result} \n')
